Spark is lazy, and that has a hidden cost. Every time you trigger an action, Spark recomputes your whole chain of transformations from scratch. If you use the same DataFrame in three places, you pay to build it three times. Caching is how you stop that waste, and to use it well, you have to understand where Spark actually keeps your data. So we'll do both, the API and the memory model behind it.

Let's start with the verbs. Cache marks a DataFrame to be kept in memory after its first computation, so later uses are instant. Persist does the same, but lets you pick exactly how the data is stored. In fact cache is just persist with the default level. And unpersist releases it, freeing that memory when you're done. That last one matters more than people think, because cached data sits around until you evict it.

When you persist, you choose a storage level, and it's a trade-off along a few axes. Memory only keeps the data as live objects in RAM. It's the fastest, but if it doesn't fit, the leftover partitions are simply recomputed on demand. Memory only serialized packs the data into compact bytes instead of objects. It saves a lot of space at the cost of some CPU to unpack it. Memory and disk is the safe default. It keeps what fits in memory and spills the rest to local disk, so nothing has to be recomputed. And memory and disk two adds replication, storing two copies across different machines, so a node failure doesn't cost you the cached data. Most of the time, memory and disk is the right choice.

Now the part that makes all of this make sense, where does cached data actually live? Picture the memory of a single executor, the JVM heap it runs in. Spark carves it into regions, and the proportions matter.

The big region, about sixty percent of the usable heap, is what's called unified memory. This is Spark's working space, and it's split between two jobs. Half of it is execution memory. That's the scratch space for the heavy lifting, the buffers used during shuffles, joins, sorts, and aggregations. The other half is storage memory. And that, right there, is where your cached blocks go, alongside broadcast variables.

The remaining forty percent is user memory. That's reserved for your own stuff, the objects and data structures your code creates, your user defined functions, and Spark's internal metadata. Spark deliberately keeps its hands off this part so your code has room to breathe. There's also a small fixed slice reserved for Spark itself, but the sixty forty split is the picture to hold in your head.

Here's the crucial insight, and the reason the word unified matters. Execution and storage don't have hard walls between them. They share that sixty percent and borrow from each other. When no caching is happening, a big shuffle can expand and use almost the whole unified region. But here's the catch. Execution memory always wins. If a shuffle needs space and the storage side is full of your cached blocks, Spark will evict those cached blocks to make room. Execution can take from storage, but storage can never starve execution.

And that single rule explains everything about choosing a storage level. If you cache with memory only, and later a big join needs execution memory, Spark throws your cached partitions away, and the next time you use that DataFrame, it silently recomputes them. You thought it was cached, but it quietly wasn't. That's why memory and disk is safer. When storage gets squeezed, your blocks spill to disk instead of vanishing, so they're always there when you need them, just a little slower to read.

So put it together. Cache when you reuse a DataFrame, and unpersist when you're done so you don't hog the storage region. Reach for memory and disk as your default, because it survives the tug of war with execution memory. And remember the shape of executor memory, sixty percent unified and shared, split between execution and your cached storage, with execution holding the right to evict. Once you can see that memory map, caching stops being magic and starts being a decision you control.
